## 3. Scope

### Release strategy

v1 is split into two coherent phases:

- **v1.0 (MVP)** — "walking skeleton." Daily-driveable end-to-end. Plain `TextEditor` editor, plain-path file refs, manual save only. No rendering toggle, no file watching, no security-scoped bookmarks. **Goal**: ship something usable in one coding pass.
- **v1.1** — five focused fixup iterations (A–E) that add the technically risky pieces on top of the MVP shell.

### v1.0 (MVP) scope

**File management**

- Multiple flat virtual folders (no nesting)
- Files added to folders via:
  - **Download button** in the bottom-left of the sidebar (opens native file picker)
  - **Drag-and-drop from Finder** onto a virtual folder in the sidebar
- File references stored as plain paths (security-scoped bookmarks added in v1.1 Iteration A)
- Files always remain in their original on-disk location; the app never moves or copies user files
- Sidebar shows virtual folders with their member files
- **Drag-reorder** of folders and files within the sidebar (visual order only — does not affect on-disk location)
- **Three-dot menu** on each sidebar file (visible on hover) with two options:
  - **Remove from app** — deletes the reference from the virtual folder; file on disk is untouched.
  - **Delete from disk** — permanently deletes the file from the user's filesystem; requires confirmation dialog
- **Missing files** — if a referenced file no longer exists on disk, the reference is silently auto-removed on next launch. (v1.1 Iteration A replaces this with inline "Locate..." UX.)

**In-app search**

- Search bar at the **top of the sidebar**
- Searches only what's already attached to the app:
  - Filenames of all files in all virtual folders
  - Markdown headings (`#`, `##`, `###`, etc.) within attached `.md` files
- For `.txt` files, search is filename-only since plaintext has no markdown headings
- Search is *not* computer-wide — to find an arbitrary file on disk, the user uses the file picker (download button) or Finder drag-drop
- Live filter as user types. Flat result list, ranked by filename relevance first, then heading relevance.

**State persistence**

- App remembers virtual folder structure, file membership and order, theme preference, and (v1.1) auto-save toggle across launches
- On launch, the previously open file (if any) is reopened automatically
- All persistence is local-only via SwiftData; no accounts, no cloud, no remote database

**Editor (MVP)**

- The selected file is **fully editable** in MVP — opening a file in the editor pane lets the user type, delete, paste, and otherwise modify its contents. Cmd+S writes the changes back to the original on-disk path.
- Edits raw markdown or plaintext — the on-disk content is always the raw source
- Plain SwiftUI `TextEditor` for the text surface
- **Editor top banner** — a SwiftUI-themed banner sits above the `TextEditor`, spanning the full width of the editor pane on the main page / for the selected file. Built natively in SwiftUI using semantic materials (`.regularMaterial` / `.bar`) so it adopts Light/Dark theming automatically. Contents in MVP:
  - The current file's display name (left-aligned)
  - A view-mode segmented control stub (disabled placeholder — wired up in v1.1 Iteration B)
  - Reserved trailing space for future actions (info, share, outline toggle) — empty in MVP
  - When no file is selected, the banner shows an empty/disabled state rather than disappearing, so the editor pane's chrome is stable
- Manual save only via Cmd+S (auto-save toggle exists in Settings as a non-functional placeholder, wired up in v1.1 Iteration C)

**Editor (v1.1, Iteration B — refines PRD v0.4)**

The original PRD described a binary toggle (raw / styled). MacMarker uses a **three-mode** model instead, accessed via a segmented control in the editor's top toolbar:

- **Raw** — SF Mono, all markdown syntax visible (`## Heading` shown as-typed).
- **Hybrid** *(default)* — SF Pro proportional, markdown syntax still visible (`## Heading` shown as-typed but in proportional font). Comfortable for prose without hiding structure.
- **Stylized** — SF Pro + formatted markdown (headings rendered larger/bolder, bold/italic styled, syntax characters hidden).

File on disk is always raw markdown regardless of mode. The mode preference is app-wide (not per-file), persisted via SwiftData.

**Auto-save (v1.1, Iteration C)**

- ON = continuous debounced save on edit
- OFF = manual save (Cmd+S) with confirmation dialog
- Default: **OFF**
- App-wide, not per-file

**Theme (Light / Dark / Device)**

- Settings scene exposes a **Light / Dark / Device** picker.
- Default: **Device** (follows system). MVP includes this — it's not deferred.
- Implementation: app-only override via SwiftUI's `.preferredColorScheme(...)`. Does not change the macOS system theme.

**Typography**

- SF Pro and SF Mono throughout, sourced from system installation
- Type scale and hierarchy aligned to the official Apple Design Resources Figma kit (token JSON shipped in repo at `assets/design/tokens/`)

**File watching (v1.1, Iteration C)**

- The app behaves as an external gatherer. External file changes **always auto-reload** into the editor, regardless of the auto-save setting.
- The auto-save toggle controls *when the user's edits are written back to disk* — it does not affect external change handling.
- **Known v1.1 limitation**: with auto-save OFF + unsaved local edits + external file change, the unsaved edits are overwritten on reload. Conflict resolution UX is deferred to v2.

**Outline pane (v1.1, Iteration D)**

A right-side third pane showing the current document's heading hierarchy, click-to-jump. Reuses the same heading parser as in-app search. Not in MVP.

**Distribution (v1.x)**

- Open-source GitHub repository
- Unsigned binary (users right-click → Open on first launch to bypass Gatekeeper)
- **Minimum macOS target**: macOS 26 only. No fallback support for earlier versions — keeps the codebase clean and gives full access to current APIs.
- App Store, signing, notarization, and licensing decisions deferred — not part of v1 scope

### Out of scope (explicitly not v1, possibly never)

Image embedding, paste, or storage. Sub-folders / nested folder structure. Computer-wide file search (Spotlight integration). Full-text content search across attached files. Tags or categories. iCloud or any cloud sync. Themes beyond Light/Dark/Device. Math formula rendering, Mermaid diagrams, code syntax highlighting. Export to PDF, Epub, or HTML. Publishing integrations (WordPress, Medium, etc.). Plugins or extensions. Mobile / iPad version. Collaborative editing. Conflict resolution UX for external changes with unsaved local edits. Version history beyond OS-level Time Machine support.

