## 4. Technical Approach

### Stack

- **Language**: Swift 6.x
- **UI shell**: SwiftUI
- **Editor pane (MVP)**: SwiftUI `TextEditor` with monospaced/proportional font roles
- **Editor pane (v1.1)**: `NSViewRepresentable`-wrapped `NSTextView`. SwiftUI's `TextEditor` cannot perform the per-line attributed styling required for the three-mode rendering toggle, so the editor pane drops to AppKit in Iteration B.
- **Persistence**: SwiftData — local-only. Stores virtual folder structure, file references, sidebar ordering, and user preferences.
- **File access (MVP)**: plain paths on `FileReference.lastKnownPath`.
- **File access (v1.1)**: security-scoped bookmarks via `URL.bookmarkData(...)` and `URL(resolvingBookmarkData:...)` — added additively in Iteration A.
- **File watching (v1.1)**: `DispatchSourceFileSystemObject` for external change detection.
- **Markdown heading extraction**: simple line-based parser (`MacMarker/Library/HeadingParser.swift`). Reused by MVP search and v1.1 outline pane.
- **Typography**: SF Pro Text, SF Pro Display, SF Mono — all system-installed.
- **Design tokens**: hand-translated from `assets/design/tokens/apple-macos-26-ui-kit.tokens.json` into `MacMarker/Resources/DesignTokens.swift`. The Swift file is the runtime source of truth.

### Toolchain

- **Editor**: VS Code with the official Swift extension (which bundles `sourcekit-lsp`)
- **Build / run / preview**: Xcode toolchain. The full Xcode application must be installed. **Day-to-day code editing happens in VS Code; Xcode is opened only for `Cmd+R` runs and SwiftUI Previews.**
- **Synchronized file groups**: the Xcode project uses `PBXFileSystemSynchronizedRootGroup` (Xcode 16+) — any Swift file added under `MacMarker/MacMarker/<subdir>/` is auto-compiled. No manual project-file edits required.

### Architecture

Standard SwiftUI app split into three primary modules:

**Library module** — manages virtual folders and file references. Owns the SwiftData model layer, sidebar UI, file-add flows (download button + drag-drop), in-app search, and three-dot menu actions.

**Editor module** — owns the editor pane (MVP: `TextEditor`; v1.1: `NSTextView` wrapper), top toolbar, three-mode rendering toggle, save logic, and file-watching behavior. Receives a file reference and operates on it.

**Settings module** — auto-save toggle, theme picker (Light/Dark/Device), persistence of user preferences. (Rendering-mode preference also lives here in v1.1.)

### Data model (SwiftData)

```swift
@Model
final class VirtualFolder {
    var id: UUID
    var name: String
    var createdAt: Date
    var order: Int
    @Relationship(deleteRule: .cascade) var files: [FileReference]
}

@Model
final class FileReference {
    var id: UUID
    var lastKnownPath: String      // primary identifier in MVP
    var displayName: String        // for sidebar; can drift from filename
    var addedAt: Date
    var order: Int                 // for drag-reorder within folder
    var folder: VirtualFolder?
    // v1.1 Iteration A adds: var bookmarkData: Data
}

@Model
final class AppState {
    var lastOpenedFileID: UUID?    // restored on launch
    var autoSaveEnabled: Bool      // default false (functional in v1.1)
    var themePreference: ThemePreference  // default .device
    // v1.1 Iteration B adds: var renderingMode: RenderingMode (default .hybrid)
}

enum ThemePreference: String, Codable { case light, dark, device }
```

### Key technical risks

- **Three-mode rendering toggle inside `NSTextView`** (v1.1 Iteration B) — applying styled text attributes to ranges of the text storage in real time, switching across Raw/Hybrid/Stylized modes without breaking selection, undo, or paste behavior. The technical centerpiece and the hardest single piece of the project.
- **macOS 26 native APIs** — newer than most AI training data covers comprehensively. Apple's documentation and the Figma kit are the authoritative sources; expect more doc-reading and experimentation than usual.
- **Security-scoped bookmark edge cases** (v1.1 Iteration A) — files moved, renamed, or on unmounted drives need graceful failure modes.
- **Heading-search performance** — parsing all attached `.md` files on every keystroke will be slow for large libraries. v1.0 does on-the-fly parsing; if perf is bad, build an in-memory index that updates when files change. Worth measuring before optimizing.

